  <!-- HOW WE TESTED -->
  <section class="problem-section">
    <div class="problem-header">
      <span class="label-pill">Buyer's guide</span>
      <h2 class="h-lg">How to evaluate <span class="accent">SEO tools for your agency.</span></h2>
      <p>If you're shopping outside this list, here's the scorecard we'd use ourselves. The five questions that separate agency tools from single-site tools.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="ba-grid">
      <div class="ba-col after" style="grid-column: 1 / -1;">
        <ul class="ba-list">
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">01</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Ask how cost scales from 5 to 50 clients — and demand a flat answer</h4>
              <p>Per-project pricing punishes growth. Tools that charge per keyword, per crawl, or per report make your margins shrink as you scale. The best agency tools have flat rates or unlimited tiers.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">02</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Separate research tools from fulfillment tools — they serve different jobs</h4>
              <p>Semrush tells you what to do. theStacc does it. Most agencies buy 3–4 tools because no single platform excels at both research and fulfillment. Know which job you're buying for.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">03</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Test the white-label experience as a client, not as an admin</h4>
              <p>Log in to the client portal as your client would. Does the dashboard look like your agency built it, or does it scream "third-party tool"? The client experience determines retention.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">04</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Calculate cost per client per month — not just total monthly spend</h4>
              <p>Semrush at $500/month looks expensive. Divided by 40 clients = $12.50 per client. theStacc Managed Services at $499/month for unlimited clients = $5 per client at 100 clients. The math looks completely different at scale.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ba-num">05</span>
            <div>
              <h4>Evaluate the content fulfillment margin — it's the highest-margin product an agency can offer</h4>
              <p>Agencies charge $500–2,000/month per client for blog content. theStacc delivers the same output for $99/client. The resell margin on content fulfillment is 5–20x. If you're not offering it, your competitors who do are winning on price.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

